metadata.name: Mediterranean #253
metadata.description:
How diverse can nature be?

Created with p5js.
Code takes a few minutes to complete. Needs a good CPU.
Works faster on Chrome browser.
For high-res images: Type a resolution multiplier number on live view. If you type 2, it will render 2 times larger than your screen size. Press "s" to save.

metadata.name: Luminous Ocean #15
metadata.description:
Luminous Ocean is a collection based on the bioluminescence phenomenon, in this case the one produced in the ocean.
I used the Flow Fields concept to create it.

There are 18 color palettes for the spheres and rings, which have 2 types of sizes, medium and small.
70% of the background is black.
20% chance that the background will change.
5% chance that the spheres and rings will be bright multicolored.
2% chance of getting a super rare ocean.

Press "S" in live mode to save image 1600x2000.

Created by Fernando. NFT License 2.0.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #24
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: ALL SEEING #58
metadata.description:
ALL SEEING explores the distribution of human eye colors by mapping color probabilities to each mint. Every artwork is different. Eye positioning, color, stroke and density is determined by a random seed hash. Color probability is loosely based on distribution across the human population, but weighted slightly to allow more color drops. For a lucky few, eyes become multicolored. If the hash gives it's blessing, there's a STAR MAN waiting in that rarest ~1% of mints that features a red background and a near fully-dialated pupil.

--- Features ---
Random eye color distributions of brown ~51% ,blue ~20%, hazel ~10%, amber ~5%, gray ~5%, green ~5%, heterochromia ~3%, and STAR MAN ~1%
Color density
White density

metadata.name: GE-I #466
metadata.description:
The first in a series of grid experiments.

Made of simple expressions of shape, color, and layout. There are 10 features including 32 pallets & 34 shape sets. The base grid is constructed of either 2x2, 4x4, 6x6, 8x8, or 20x20 layouts.

metadata.name: SuperCube 1000 #652
metadata.description:
Celebrating 1000 projects on fxhash by releasing 1000 unique editions for free.

This is a tribute to Victor Vasarely (1906-1997), whom I consider to be one of the fathers of the generative art movement, and whose art was very present in the house I grew up in as a child.
